The article discusses the progress made in lowering healthcare costs for seniors and their families through Medicare. Starting from January 1, 2024, prescription drug costs will become more affordable due to the Inflation Reduction Act. Seniors with high drug spending will have their out-of-pocket costs capped at around $3,500 next year, and all enrollees will have their costs capped at $2,000 in 2025. Low-income seniors and disabled individuals will receive extra help through the expanded Low Income Subsidy program. Additionally, the price of insulin has been capped at $35 per month, and recommended vaccines are now free for Medicare beneficiaries. The article highlights the efforts of Congressional Democrats in delivering these cost savings, contrasting it with the Republican opposition. The author vows to continue fighting to lower healthcare costs and protect Medicare for future generations.